<img class="left" src="img/sulfur-bohr.gif" width="100px" />Sulfur is the chemical element that has the atomic number 16. It is a widely-found non-metal that has been known about throughout human history. It can be found in nature as a pure element as well as in its sulfide and sulfate (mineral) forms. Sulfur is an essential element in life - it's a minor component of fats, body fluids, and skeletal minerals. It's also used very widely for man-made purposes; including as a component of fertilizers, gunpowder, matches, insecticides, pesticides, and fungicides.
